C'est le paradis... #

911
01:00:08,860 --> 01:00:11,260
Do you still feel like a schoolgirl?

912
01:00:17,320 --> 01:00:19,320
It wasn’t too uncomfortable?

913
01:00:20,020 --> 01:00:22,100
Not after the first bit.

914
01:00:24,820 --> 01:00:26,870
It’s funny, though, isn’t it?

915
01:00:30,310 --> 01:00:33,360
All that poetry, and all those songs

916
01:00:34,400 --> 01:00:37,050
about something that lasts no time
at all?

917
01:00:38,510 --> 01:00:39,360
Yeah.

918
01:00:42,250 --> 01:00:45,450
All your exercise books on my desk
in a pile, please.

919
01:00:48,210 --> 01:00:49,910
I bought this for you.

920
01:00:54,860 --> 01:00:56,660
That's very kind of you.

921
01:01:00,160 --> 01:01:01,860
But I can't accept it.

922
01:01:03,030 --> 01:01:04,030
Why not?

923
01:01:05,930 --> 01:01:09,070
It’s because of people like you that
I plough through illiterate essays

924
01:01:09,120 --> 01:01:11,320
by Sandra Lovell about her pony.

925
01:01:12,920 --> 01:01:15,470
But I know where this comes from,
Jenny.

926
01:01:15,820 --> 01:01:20,080
And If I took it, I'll feel like I'd
be betraying both of us.

927
01:01:34,650 --> 01:01:35,550
Jenny.

928
01:01:39,500 --> 01:01:42,250
You can do anything you want. You
know that.

929
01:01:43,180 --> 01:01:45,480
You’re clever and you’re pretty...

930
01:01:48,710 --> 01:01:51,680
Is your boyfriend interested in
clever Jenny?

931
01:01:53,520 --> 01:01:55,290
I’m not quite sure what you’re
trying to tell me.

932
01:01:55,340 --> 01:01:58,290
I’m telling you to go to Oxford. No
matter what.

933
01:02:00,240 --> 01:02:02,940
'Cause if you don't, you’ll break my
heart.

934
01:02:09,580 --> 01:02:11,030
Where did you go?

935
01:02:11,560 --> 01:02:12,660
Cambridge.

936
01:02:12,920 --> 01:02:15,420
Well. You’re clever. And you’re
pretty.

937
01:02:15,480 --> 01:02:17,130
So presumably, Clever Miss Stubbs
won.

938
01:02:17,180 --> 01:02:19,680
And here you are with your pony
essays.

939
01:02:19,800 --> 01:02:22,900
I don't know. These last few months,
I’ve eaten in wonderful restaurants,

940
01:02:22,950 --> 01:02:26,000
and went to jazz clubs, and watch
wonderful films,

941
01:02:26,470 --> 01:02:28,270
heard beautiful music...

942
01:02:30,120 --> 01:02:33,770
- Jenny, you're taking precautions.
- Nothing to do with that.

943
01:02:33,820 --> 01:02:34,420
Isn’t it?

944
01:02:34,470 --> 01:02:38,420
Maybe will our lives going to end up
with pony essays. Or housework.

945
01:02:39,080 --> 01:02:40,630
And yes, maybe we’ll go to Oxford.

946
01:02:40,680 --> 01:02:42,290
But if we’re all going to die
the moment we graduate,

947
01:02:42,340 --> 01:02:44,940
Isn't it what we do before that
counts.

948
01:02:49,840 --> 01:02:51,890
I’m sorry you think I’m dead.

949
01:02:54,200 --> 01:02:55,810
I don’t think you’re dead. I just...

950
01:02:55,860 --> 01:02:58,610
I think you’d better get to your
next class.

951
01:03:15,840 --> 01:03:17,290
Well done, Jenny.

952
01:03:17,480 --> 01:03:20,040
I haven't won anything before. Not
even at the raffle.

953
01:03:20,090 --> 01:03:21,310
Oh, you've bet on the sweetest
looking one,

954
01:03:21,360 --> 01:03:22,220
and he always comes last.

955
01:03:22,270 --> 01:03:24,250
- Let's go. - Come on. - Oh, can we
do it again? I'm feeling lucky!

956
01:03:24,300 --> 01:03:25,790
Come on. Let's go. I don't want to
miss him.

957
01:03:25,840 --> 01:03:29,340
Pick up your 10 bob on your way out.
- I won ten shillings!

958
01:03:29,530 --> 01:03:31,330
Who is this man, anyway?

959
01:03:31,430 --> 01:03:33,880
- Peter Rachman.
- A complete bastard.

960
01:03:33,980 --> 01:03:36,150
Why do you have to see him here?

961
01:03:36,200 --> 01:03:39,400
Because he's not a sort of chap
with an office.

962
01:03:42,100 --> 01:03:43,650
<i>- All right?
- Yeah.</i>

963
01:03:44,830 --> 01:03:46,030
Ladies...

964
01:03:53,850 --> 01:03:56,440
A bottle of your finest champagne,
please.

965
01:03:56,490 --> 01:03:57,690
There he is.

966
01:04:02,340 --> 01:04:04,820
Come on, Jenny. Tell them your good
news. Don’t be bashful.

967
01:04:04,870 --> 01:04:06,300
No. Be Sneezy.

968
01:04:07,050 --> 01:04:09,580
Jenny got two A's and a B in her
mock-A levels.

969
01:04:09,630 --> 01:04:11,720
Like everyone else in this
sophisticated establishment.

970
01:04:11,770 --> 01:04:13,220
The B was in Latin.

971
01:04:13,270 --> 01:04:15,920
- Seriously. Congratulations.
- Excuse us.

972
01:04:21,390 --> 01:04:23,040
Don’t worry too much.

973
01:04:24,270 --> 01:04:25,420
About what?

974
01:04:26,030 --> 01:04:27,530
Someone told me that in about fifty
years

975
01:04:27,580 --> 01:04:29,400
no one will speak Latin, probably.

976
01:04:29,450 --> 01:04:32,550
Not even Latin people. So don't
worry about your B.

977
01:04:38,600 --> 01:04:40,330
He's even more of a bastard than
I thought!

978
01:04:40,380 --> 01:04:42,410
You don't want him to marry your
sister.

979
01:04:42,460 --> 01:04:45,510
Or want to talk to him in a club,
come to that.

980
01:04:46,160 --> 01:04:49,310
You do know what you’re doing, old
chap? With Jenny?

981
01:04:50,240 --> 01:04:52,490
- This is the one, Danny.
- Right.

982
01:04:55,620 --> 01:04:57,470
You see, she’s different.

983
01:04:58,030 --> 01:05:00,330
I just don’t want to see her hurt.

984
01:05:24,960 --> 01:05:27,140
Have you bought any more paintings
recently?

985
01:05:27,190 --> 01:05:28,590
Have I? Yes.

986
01:05:29,520 --> 01:05:31,470
I picked up a little Piper.

987
01:05:31,690 --> 01:05:32,500
A good one, I think.

988
01:05:32,550 --> 01:05:34,800
I’m still trying to work out what
makes good things good.

989
01:05:34,850 --> 01:05:35,910
It’s hard, isn’t it?

990
01:05:35,960 --> 01:05:38,445
The thing is, Jenny, you know,

991
01:05:39,620 --> 01:05:43,520
without necessarily being able to
explain why. See, You have taste.

992
01:05:44,650 --> 01:05:48,090
That’s not half the battle. That’s
the whole war.

993
01:06:09,470 --> 01:06:11,620
Jenny, we should go. It’s late.

994
01:06:11,820 --> 01:06:13,090
- Really?
- Yeah.

995
01:06:13,140 --> 01:06:15,840
Alas. One day, school will be over
forever,

996
01:06:15,950 --> 01:06:17,760
we can talk about art all night.

997
01:06:17,810 --> 01:06:19,930
You’re all right in a taxi, aren’t
you?

998
01:06:19,980 --> 01:06:21,750
Yeah. I'm fine.

999
01:06:22,010 --> 01:06:23,510
Let's go. Come on.

1000
01:06:25,260 --> 01:06:26,410
Good night.

1001
01:06:33,140 --> 01:06:34,240
Wait here.

1002
01:06:40,040 --> 01:06:41,520
David, what are you looking for?

1003
01:06:41,570 --> 01:06:43,370
It's just...

1004
01:06:46,210 --> 01:06:47,760
What are you doing?

1005
01:06:49,720 --> 01:06:51,220
Will you marry me?

1006
01:06:52,780 --> 01:06:54,680
What were you looking for?

1007
01:06:55,080 --> 01:06:56,830
I thought I had a ring.

1008
01:06:57,280 --> 01:07:00,850
It wouldn’t have been the right one.
But it would have done for tonight.

1009
01:07:00,900 --> 01:07:02,130
Oh, David.

1010
01:07:04,130 --> 01:07:05,330
I’m serious.

1011
01:07:11,040 --> 01:07:12,540
You’re very sweet.

1012
01:07:14,920 --> 01:07:16,420
What do you think?

1013
01:07:23,270 --> 01:07:24,520
Take me home.

1014
01:07:24,790 --> 01:07:25,890
All right.

1015
01:07:52,820 --> 01:07:54,390
<i>They do need some looking after,</i>

1016
01:07:54,440 --> 01:07:56,610
<i>but nothing that will require too
much work.</i>

1017
01:07:56,660 --> 01:07:59,170
<i>Just leave them in your potting shed
for a couple of weeks,</i>

1018
01:07:59,220 --> 01:08:00,520
<i>and they’ll look after themselves.</i>

1019
01:08:00,570 --> 01:08:01,970
Fine. The potting shed.

1020
01:08:02,020 --> 01:08:05,020
Who does he think I am? Prince
Rainier of Monaco?

1021
01:08:08,510 --> 01:08:11,560
What if I got married instead of
going to college?

1022
01:08:11,780 --> 01:08:12,780
Married?

1023
01:08:12,910 --> 01:08:13,910
Married.

1024
01:08:15,470 --> 01:08:17,630
Well. It would depend who it was, of
course.

1025
01:08:17,680 --> 01:08:20,070
Would it? That’s interesting.

1026
01:08:20,190 --> 01:08:23,580
Of course it'd. I wouldn’t want you
married off just for the sake of it.

1027
01:08:23,630 --> 01:08:24,280
Thanks.

1028
01:08:24,330 --> 01:08:25,830
<i>Has somebody asked you?</i>

1029
01:08:25,880 --> 01:08:26,680
Yes.

1030
01:08:27,230 --> 01:08:28,030
Who?

1031
01:08:29,720 --> 01:08:30,570
<i>David?</i>

1032
01:08:30,620 --> 01:08:33,020
No. A man I just met walking his
dog.

1033
01:08:33,470 --> 01:08:34,920
What did you tell him?

1034
01:08:34,970 --> 01:08:36,170
Nothing yet.

1035
01:08:37,180 --> 01:08:39,730
Do you have a choice? Or is it too
late.

1036
01:08:40,270 --> 01:08:44,700
Of course she’s got a choice.
An interesting one, too, eh?

1037
01:08:44,780 --> 01:08:47,970
This is where you’re supposed to
say, “But what about Oxford?”

1038
01:08:48,020 --> 01:08:50,170
Well. Looked at it another way,

1039
01:08:50,310 --> 01:08:53,160
you wouldn’t really need to go now,
would you?

1040
01:08:53,380 --> 01:08:57,080
I wouldn’t need to go. Would you
like to expand on that?

1041
01:08:57,290 --> 01:08:59,080
You'd been looking after.

1042
01:08:59,130 --> 01:09:04,240
All that Latin! All those essays!
What was the point?

1043
01:09:04,610 --> 01:09:07,010
Why didn’t you just send me prowling
round nightclubs?

1044
01:09:07,060 --> 01:09:09,050
It would have been less trouble. And
I might have had more fun.

1045
01:09:09,100 --> 01:09:12,290
I don’t know about nightclubs.
I know about education.

1046
01:09:12,340 --> 01:09:14,980
Anyway, it looks like it might
have turned out for the best.

1047
01:09:15,030 --> 01:09:15,860
How?

1048
01:09:17,210 --> 01:09:20,210
He wouldn’t want you if you were
thick, would he?

1049
01:09:20,970 --> 01:09:23,890
<i>May not an ass know when the cart
draws the horse?</i>

1050
01:09:23,940 --> 01:09:26,040
Sings whoop jug I love thee.

1051
01:09:26,090 --> 01:09:30,750
And when it says "Sings", it means
you sing a line.

1052
01:09:33,590 --> 01:09:35,210
Never mind. Right. Lear...

1053
01:09:35,260 --> 01:09:38,030
Does any here know me.
This is not Lear.

1054
01:09:38,120 --> 01:09:42,740
<i>Does Lear walk thus? Speak thus?
Where are his eyes?</i>

1055
01:09:44,140 --> 01:09:48,580
Ha! Waking? Who is it that can tell
me who I am?

1056
01:09:48,710 --> 01:09:50,750
Ooh. Miss. Me. I can.

1057
01:09:52,690 --> 01:09:53,790
Oh, Jenny.

1058
01:09:54,960 --> 01:09:55,810
What?

1059
01:09:58,790 --> 01:09:59,990
Take it off.

1060
01:10:02,310 --> 01:10:04,870
Oh my God. Is that what I think it
is?

1061
01:10:05,490 --> 01:10:07,540
<i>I'm going to be a bridesmaid!</i>

1062
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:11,650
You know the school rule on jewelry.

1063
01:10:11,700 --> 01:10:13,360
Half the girls in this room are
wearing jewelry.

1064
01:10:13,410 --> 01:10:16,410
Yes. But none of it is going to ruin
their lives.

1065
01:10:18,160 --> 01:10:20,860
We have a difference of opinion
about that.

1066
01:10:23,720 --> 01:10:26,120
How far advanced are these
ridiculous plans?

1067
01:10:26,170 --> 01:10:29,220
Have you set a date? Have you
decided on a church?

1068
01:10:29,280 --> 01:10:32,630
We won’t be getting married in a
church. David’s Jewish.

1069
01:10:34,250 --> 01:10:38,070
Jewish? He’s a Jew?

1070
01:10:40,640 --> 01:10:43,290
You’re aware, I take it, that the
Jews killed our Lord?

1071
01:10:43,340 --> 01:10:46,590
And you’re aware, I suppose, that
our Lord was Jewish?

1072
01:10:47,660 --> 01:10:49,610
I suppose he told you that.

1073
01:10:51,280 --> 01:10:54,160
We’re all very sorry about what
happened at during the War.

1074
01:10:54,210 --> 01:10:57,360
But that’s absolutely no excuse for
that sort of malicious

1075
01:10:57,410 --> 01:10:59,400
and untruthful propaganda.

1076
01:10:59,920 --> 01:11:02,690
Anyway, I can see you are far more in
need of responsible advice

1077
01:11:02,740 --> 01:11:04,140
than I realised.

1078
01:11:05,530 --> 01:11:08,580
Nobody does anything worth doing
without a degree.

1079
01:11:09,510 --> 01:11:13,410
Nobody does anything worth doing
with the degree. No woman, anyway.

1080
01:11:13,570 --> 01:11:15,370
So what I do isn’t worth doing.

1081
01:11:15,420 --> 01:11:18,370
Or what Miss Stubbs does, or Mrs
Wilson, or any of us here.

1082
01:11:18,420 --> 01:11:20,140
Because none of us would be here
without the degree,

1083
01:11:20,190 --> 01:11:21,170
you do realise that, don’t you?

1084
01:11:21,220 --> 01:11:23,250
And yes, of course studying is hard,
and boring...

1085
01:11:23,300 --> 01:11:24,250
Boring!

1086
01:11:24,740 --> 01:11:25,270
I’m sorry?

1087
01:11:25,320 --> 01:11:28,900
Studying is hard and boring.
Teaching is hard and boring

1088
01:11:28,950 --> 01:11:31,440
So what you’re telling me is to be
bored, and then bored,

1089
01:11:31,490 --> 01:11:34,440
and finally bored again, but this
time for the rest of my life.

1090
01:11:34,490 --> 01:11:36,980
This whole stupid country is bored.

1091
01:11:37,150 --> 01:11:39,750
There’s no life in it, or colour,
or fun.

1092
01:11:40,320 --> 01:11:42,010
It’s probably just as well that the
Russians are going to drop

1093
01:11:42,060 --> 01:11:43,340
a nuclear bomb on us any day now.

1094
01:11:43,390 --> 01:11:50,140
So my choice is to do something hard
and boring, or to marry my Jew,

1095
01:11:50,530 --> 01:11:53,610
and go to Paris and Rome and listen
to jazz

1096
01:11:53,880 --> 01:11:57,430
and read and eat good food in nice
restaurants and have fun.

1097
01:11:58,350 --> 01:12:00,450
It’s not enough to educate us any
more, Mrs Walters.

1098
01:12:00,500 --> 01:12:03,150
You’ve got to tell us why you’re
doing it.

1099
01:12:05,510 --> 01:12:07,980
It doesn’t have to be teaching,
you know.

1100
01:12:08,030 --> 01:12:09,930
There’s the Civil Service.

1101
01:12:13,840 --> 01:12:16,590
I don’t wish to be impertinent,
Mrs Walters.

1102
01:12:16,950 --> 01:12:19,450
But it is an argument worth
rehearsing.

1103
01:12:20,070 --> 01:12:22,240
You never know. Someone else might
want to know the point of it all,

1104
01:12:22,290 --> 01:12:23,290
one day.

1105
01:13:11,600 --> 01:13:13,300
<i>Where did you find him?</i>

1106
01:13:13,350 --> 01:13:14,420
<i>- I can't tell you that.
- Why?</i>

1107
01:13:14,470 --> 01:13:16,120
<i>I think he likes you--- Do you like
her?</i>

1108
01:13:16,170 --> 01:13:17,200
"I thought you would like her."

1109
01:13:17,250 --> 01:13:18,940
You do... you don't...

1110
01:13:18,990 --> 01:13:21,610
You don't remember? It's Jenny! You
remember her from the last time?

1111
01:13:21,660 --> 01:13:23,510
"No. I don't"
Yes, you do.

1112
01:13:23,970 --> 01:13:26,360
You're naughty! You're pardoned?
You're naughty.

1113
01:13:26,410 --> 01:13:28,460
Go stick to your own species.

1114
01:13:28,820 --> 01:13:31,030
He wants to kiss you, I think.

1115
01:13:31,620 --> 01:13:33,470
Isn't that naughty?
- Yes.

1116
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:35,000
We're engaged.

1117
01:13:35,050 --> 01:13:38,200
<i>Seriously? No. Really?</i>

1118
01:13:38,270 --> 01:13:40,150
- Yeah. - Engaged? - Show her.

1119
01:13:40,200 --> 01:13:41,300
Yes. Look!

1120
01:13:41,570 --> 01:13:44,300
Gosh. That’s fantastic news.

1121
01:13:44,350 --> 01:13:45,880
Ooh, thank you.

1122
01:13:46,660 --> 01:13:47,530
Congratulations.

1123
01:13:47,580 --> 01:13:50,030
I knew you’d see sense about
university. You’ll stay pretty now.

1124
01:13:50,080 --> 01:13:52,140
Thank you. Can I still read?

1125
01:13:52,490 --> 01:13:54,630
Of course. But it doesn't have to be
books, does it?

1126
01:13:54,680 --> 01:13:57,770
And magazines will do just as well.
And you learn more from them anyway.

1127
01:13:57,820 --> 01:13:58,920
Oh, Helen.

1128
01:13:59,180 --> 01:14:03,330
<i>You won’t be laughing, David, when
she gets all speccy and spotty.</i>

1129
01:14:10,160 --> 01:14:12,670
Danny didn’t seem very pleased
about our engagement.

1130
01:14:12,720 --> 01:14:16,170
I've noticed that, too. Thought he
might be a bit jealous.

1131
01:14:16,390 --> 01:14:17,390
Jealous?

1132
01:14:18,100 --> 01:14:20,550
We're going to keep him away from
you.

1133
01:14:27,170 --> 01:14:29,910
I mean, what is supposed to order
for starter, anyway?

1134
01:14:29,960 --> 01:14:32,080
And how will I know what is a
starter, or what is it not?

1135
01:14:32,130 --> 01:14:33,590
We’ve been through this, Dad.

1136
01:14:33,640 --> 01:14:36,290
It’ll be quite clearly marked on
the menu.

1137
01:14:36,840 --> 01:14:38,930
Can’t the three of you just go on
your own. Leave me here.

1138
01:14:38,980 --> 01:14:41,780
I’ll be perfectly happy with a tin
of seven.

1139
01:14:45,380 --> 01:14:46,780
- Hello.
- Hello.

1140
01:14:51,870 --> 01:14:54,010
Ready?
I think you’ll like this place, Jack.

1141
01:14:54,060 --> 01:14:56,040
Their wine list is as good as
anything I’ve seen in London.

1142
01:14:56,090 --> 01:14:57,980
Yes. Someone told me that.

1143
01:14:58,030 --> 01:15:00,830
David, probably. Who else would it
have been?

1144
01:15:02,820 --> 01:15:03,900
Madam.

1145
01:15:04,390 --> 01:15:06,000
I was hoping you’d take us in this.

1146
01:15:06,050 --> 01:15:08,330
Hey, you won’t want to drive in
anything else after tonight.

1147
01:15:08,380 --> 01:15:10,630
Mind you, it drinks petrol.
- Yes.

1148
01:15:10,910 --> 01:15:14,060
I’m afraid We’ll have to stop on the
way in to town.

1149
01:15:14,720 --> 01:15:16,670
- I feel like Eamonn Andrews.
- Is that a good thing?

1150
01:15:16,720 --> 01:15:20,520
Eamonn Andrews is the poshest person
that Jack can imagine being.

1151
01:15:34,850 --> 01:15:37,300
How are you tonight, sir?
- Very well.

1152
01:15:37,920 --> 01:15:40,020
You might as well fill her up.

1153
01:15:40,390 --> 01:15:43,690
I'm going to make a quick call. I’ll
be two ticks.

1154
01:15:50,350 --> 01:15:53,850
Do you think I should offer to help
pay for the petrol?

1155
01:15:54,110 --> 01:15:56,630
Would he be insulted, what do you
think?

1156
01:15:56,680 --> 01:15:58,600
I know, he said tonight was his
treat.

1157
01:15:58,650 --> 01:16:01,050
But does that apply to the petrol,
what do you think?

1158
01:16:01,140 --> 01:16:03,240
I'm quiet sure, it does, Jack.

1159
01:16:10,920 --> 01:16:13,370
- Jack!
- Come on! It just came off.

1160
01:16:22,460 --> 01:16:24,720
<i>- Filled my bill?
- Thank you, sir.</i>

1161
01:16:24,770 --> 01:16:25,720
Cheers.

1162
01:16:29,400 --> 01:16:30,760
Jenny. Jenny...

1163
01:16:31,960 --> 01:16:33,320
Take us home.

1164
01:16:33,460 --> 01:16:34,710
<i>What’s wrong?</i>

1165
01:16:35,250 --> 01:16:37,490
I'm afraid there’s been--- Jenny's
had a bit of a shock.

1166
01:16:37,540 --> 01:16:40,608
What’s happened? - It’s just another
one of David’s little muddles

1167
01:16:40,658 --> 01:16:42,358
<i>and misunderstandings.</i>

1168
01:16:43,850 --> 01:16:46,110
I don’t want to hear another word
from anybody. Take us home. Now.

1169
01:16:46,160 --> 01:16:47,260
Fine.

1170
01:16:58,140 --> 01:16:59,760
<i>You can take care of this, can’t you,
David?</i>

1171
01:16:59,810 --> 01:17:01,260
Go inside, Dad.

1172
01:17:06,010 --> 01:17:07,860
Mr and Mrs David Goldman,

1173
01:17:08,140 --> 01:17:09,740
Mr and Mrs David Goldman,

1174
01:17:09,790 --> 01:17:12,140
Mr and Mrs David--- You’re married!

1175
01:17:13,710 --> 01:17:15,310
Legally, yes, but...

1176
01:17:15,750 --> 01:17:17,140
When were you going to tell me?

1177
01:17:17,190 --> 01:17:20,800
Soon. It just never seemed the right
time.

1178
01:17:24,880 --> 01:17:26,690
You seemed so happy, and I was
happy, and...

1179
01:17:26,740 --> 01:17:29,590
You were living with your wife! All
this time!

1180
01:17:30,290 --> 01:17:32,510
Round the corner. Byron Avenue.

1181
01:17:32,560 --> 01:17:34,700
It’s no wonder we kept bumping into
each other, then, is it?

1182
01:17:34,750 --> 01:17:37,250
What number?
- Thirty four.

1183
01:17:42,970 --> 01:17:44,970
Don't be like this. Come on.

1184
01:17:48,740 --> 01:17:55,720
I have nothing. I didn’t take my
exams. I do--- I left school.

1185
01:17:57,870 --> 01:17:59,720
Where’s it all gone, now?

1186
01:18:01,130 --> 01:18:02,730
I can get a divorce.

1187
01:18:05,970 --> 01:18:08,420
Everything will turn out for the
best.

1188
01:18:17,260 --> 01:18:18,710
Go and tell them.

1189
01:18:21,750 --> 01:18:24,550
Go and tell them, then go and tell
your wife.

1190
01:18:25,430 --> 01:18:28,110
They won't listen now. All right?

1191
01:18:29,000 --> 01:18:33,350
I'll come round tomorrow. When
everyone’s a bit calmer.

1192
01:18:33,640 --> 01:18:37,410
Please don’t make me tell them on my
own.

1193
01:18:38,260 --> 01:18:40,680
You owe me that much. You owe them
that much.

1194
01:18:40,730 --> 01:18:42,880
I owe them much more than that.

1195
01:18:49,300 --> 01:18:50,100
Hey.

1196
01:19:05,270 --> 01:19:08,420
Two minutes. And I’ll come out and
drag you in.

1197
01:20:03,700 --> 01:20:05,100
What’s going on?

1198
01:20:08,720 --> 01:20:12,320
He’s helping himself to some Dutch
courage before facing you.

1199
01:20:13,220 --> 01:20:15,870
Stolen Dutch courage, from the look
of it.

1200
01:20:17,500 --> 01:20:19,900
He has something he has to tell you.

1201
01:20:31,380 --> 01:20:32,880
He just drove off.

1202
01:20:38,990 --> 01:20:40,390
Can you tell us?

1203
01:20:42,890 --> 01:20:44,190
Jenny? Please?

1204
01:20:50,050 --> 01:20:52,400
<i>I wouldn't worry about it too much.</i>

1205
01:20:54,770 --> 01:20:57,120
When I found out---
- Not now Helen!

1206
01:21:05,760 --> 01:21:07,360
<i>I tried to tell him.</i>

1207
01:21:09,140 --> 01:21:12,440
I’m not speaking to him now, if
that’s any consolation.

1208
01:21:15,570 --> 01:21:18,020
It's a funny world you people live
in.

1209
01:21:19,390 --> 01:21:21,680
You both watched me carrying on with
a married man,

1210
01:21:21,730 --> 01:21:23,250
you don’t think it’s worth saying
anything about.

1211
01:21:23,300 --> 01:21:25,850
Please, if you want that
conversation...

1212
01:21:26,270 --> 01:21:29,050
You watched David and I help
ourselves to a map,

1213
01:21:29,100 --> 01:21:31,300
and you didn’t say much, either.

1214
01:21:57,450 --> 01:22:00,070
Come on you. Let's go. Good boy.

1215
01:22:08,310 --> 01:22:09,210
Hello.

1216
01:22:10,970 --> 01:22:14,360
Hello. Sorry, I think I have a wrong
number. I was looking for my...

1217
01:22:14,410 --> 01:22:16,760
I wanted number of my cello lesson.

1218
01:22:20,960 --> 01:22:22,660
Oh, no. Don’t tell me.

1219
01:22:24,250 --> 01:22:27,160
Good God. You're a child.

1220
01:22:31,620 --> 01:22:34,880
You didn’t know about any of this.
Presumably.

1221
01:22:38,970 --> 01:22:40,470
No. They never do.

1222
01:22:44,960 --> 01:22:47,360
You’re not in the family way, are
you?

1223
01:22:47,410 --> 01:22:49,560
Because that’s happened before.

1224
01:22:53,970 --> 01:22:55,520
Thank God for that.

1225
01:22:59,380 --> 01:23:01,080
No, no, you stay here.

1226
01:23:13,040 --> 01:23:15,390
- Did you see her?
- Yes. I saw her.

1227
01:23:16,520 --> 01:23:18,530
I didn’t talk to her. There wasn’t
any need.

1228
01:23:18,580 --> 01:23:20,430
We have to have this out.

1229
01:23:22,090 --> 01:23:24,110
If you won’t do it, I will. I’m
still your father.

1230
01:23:24,160 --> 01:23:26,260
Oh, you’re my father again, are you?

1231
01:23:26,310 --> 01:23:29,810
What were you when you encouraged me
to throw my life away?

1232
01:23:30,290 --> 01:23:32,910
Silly schoolgirls are always getting
seduced by glamorous older men.

1233
01:23:32,960 --> 01:23:34,510
What about you two?

1234
01:24:03,310 --> 01:24:04,210
Jenny?

1235
01:24:11,180 --> 01:24:12,080
Jenny?

1236
01:24:17,080 --> 01:24:18,530
Jenny, I'm sorry.

1237
01:24:26,750 --> 01:24:29,200
I know I've made a mess of
everything.

1238
01:24:36,560 --> 01:24:41,970
All my life I’ve been scared,
I didn’t want you to be scared.

1239
01:24:45,450 --> 01:24:48,000
That’s why I wanted you to go to
Oxford.

1240
01:24:49,270 --> 01:24:53,310
<i>And then along came David...
he knew famous writers,</i>

1241
01:24:53,360 --> 01:24:56,360
<i>he knew how to get to classical
music concerts...</i>

1242
01:25:01,170 --> 01:25:03,420
<i>But he wasn’t who he said he was.</i>

1243
01:25:06,180 --> 01:25:08,630
<i>He wasn’t who you said he was,
either.</i>

1244
01:25:17,400 --> 01:25:19,660
The other day, your mother and I
were listening to...

1245
01:25:19,710 --> 01:25:22,960
a programme on the radio about
CS Lewis, and they said

1246
01:25:23,410 --> 01:25:26,440
that he moved to Cambridge in 1954.

1247
01:25:29,920 --> 01:25:32,520
<i>I said, Well, they’ve got that wrong,</i>

1248
01:25:35,500 --> 01:25:38,300
<i>our Jenny wouldn't have his name
in her book,</i>

1249
01:25:39,950 --> 01:25:41,800
<i>if he moved to Cambridge.</i>

1250
01:25:51,320 --> 01:25:54,320
There’s a cup of tea, and some
biscuits out here.

1251
01:26:25,930 --> 01:26:27,980
How do you think we can help?

1252
01:26:30,460 --> 01:26:34,010
I want to repeat my last year at
school.  And take my exams.

1253
01:26:35,530 --> 01:26:37,590
I got the impression the last time
we spoke

1254
01:26:37,640 --> 01:26:39,740
that you didn’t see the point of
school.

1255
01:26:39,790 --> 01:26:41,940
Or of me, or of any of us here.

1256
01:26:42,490 --> 01:26:44,140
I know. I was stupid.

1257
01:26:44,850 --> 01:26:47,750
The life I want, there's no
shortcut.

1258
01:26:49,580 --> 01:26:52,530
I know now, that I need to go to the
university.

1259
01:26:53,600 --> 01:26:56,360
It gives me absolutely no pleasure
whatsoever

1260
01:26:56,410 --> 01:26:59,710
to see our young schoolgirls
throwing their lives away.

1261
01:27:00,340 --> 01:27:03,030
Although, of course, you’re not one
of our schoolgirls any more.

1262
01:27:03,080 --> 01:27:04,980
Through your own volition.

1263
01:27:05,490 --> 01:27:08,080
I suppose you think I’m a ruined
woman.

1264
01:27:10,160 --> 01:27:11,710
You’re not a woman.

1265
01:27:13,550 --> 01:27:16,100
<i>No, I'm afraid, I think that the
offer of a place at this school</i>

1266
01:27:16,150 --> 01:27:17,900
<i>would be wasted on you.</i>

1267
01:27:42,710 --> 01:27:43,710
Come in.

1268
01:27:46,250 --> 01:27:48,500
<i>I didn't expect to see you again.</i>

1269
01:27:56,200 --> 01:27:57,550
This is lovely.

1270
01:27:58,440 --> 01:28:00,740
All your books and pictures and...

1271
01:28:02,610 --> 01:28:04,810
Paperbacks and postcards, Jenny.

1272
01:28:06,100 --> 01:28:08,100
It’s all you need, isn’t it?

1273
01:28:10,890 --> 01:28:12,490
Just somewhere to...

1274
01:28:21,480 --> 01:28:25,390
I’m sorry I said those silly things.
I didn’t understand.

1275
01:28:29,530 --> 01:28:31,230
Let’s forget about it.

1276
01:28:39,540 --> 01:28:41,020
A Burne-Jones.

1277
01:28:42,130 --> 01:28:43,530
Do you like him?

1278
01:28:43,580 --> 01:28:45,640
I do. Still.

1279
01:28:47,670 --> 01:28:51,380
Still? You sound very old and wise.

1280
01:28:54,480 --> 01:28:57,590
I feel old. But not very wise.

1281
01:29:03,410 --> 01:29:05,510
Miss Stubbs, I need your help.

1282
01:29:10,950 --> 01:29:14,000
I was so hoping that’s what you were
going to say.

1283
01:30:02,250 --> 01:30:03,850
Thank you, Marjorie.

1284
01:30:18,570 --> 01:30:20,020
It's from Oxford.

1285
01:30:53,950 --> 01:30:58,430
<i>It is my pleasure to inform you that
your application to read English</i>

1286
01:30:58,550 --> 01:31:00,660
<i>at Oxford has been accepted.</i>

1287
01:31:01,880 --> 01:31:05,590
<i>On behalf of the Faculty of Arts,
staff of the university...</i>

1288
01:31:26,250 --> 01:31:28,500
<i>So I went to read English books,</i>

1289
01:31:28,750 --> 01:31:31,000
<i>and did my best to avoid the speccy,
spotty fate</i>

1290
01:31:31,050 --> 01:31:33,050
<i>that Helen predicted for me.</i>

1291
01:31:33,570 --> 01:31:36,750
<i>I probably looked as wide-eyed,
fresh, and artless</i>

1292
01:31:36,860 --> 01:31:38,610
<i>as any other student.</i>

1293
01:31:39,150 --> 01:31:40,400
<i>But I wasn't.</i>

1294
01:31:42,320 --> 01:31:43,840
<i>One of the boys I went out with---</i>

1295
01:31:43,890 --> 01:31:45,760
<i>and they really were boys,</i>

1296
01:31:45,810 --> 01:31:48,260
<i>once asked me to go to Paris with
him.</i>

1297
01:31:48,730 --> 01:31:52,570
<i>And I told him. And I'd love to,
I was dying to see Paris.</i>

1298
01:31:54,540 --> 01:31:56,240
<i>As if I'd never been.</i>

1299
